english:
  title: The Biography of Paper
  author: Lee Cheom
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Paper bore the name White, with the courtesy name Unstained, and hailed from Kuaiji. He was descended from Cai Lun, that great innovator of the Han court. At his birth, he was bathed in fragrant waters and adorned with white jade—thus his pristine nature. Nineteen brothers shared his mother's womb, and all dwelt in harmony, never breaking rank even in haste. By temperament he was fastidious and gentle, shunning warriors, preferring the company of scholars. Mao the Brush Scholar was his intimate friend, and though Paper's face might be marked with ink, he would not wipe it away.

    His learning encompassed the principles of heaven and earth, the sources of sage wisdom, the hundred schools of thought, and even the teachings of heterodox sects—all recorded with perfect recall. When the Han held examinations for upright men, Paper presented himself and declared: "Since ancient times, we have bound bamboo strips and silken cloth for writing—both inconvenient. Though I am but humble, let me offer my heart as replacement. Should I fail, mark me as you will."

    The Emperor tested him, and Paper proved able to remember all without error—a thousand words, not one forgotten. Thus did he receive the title of Minister of White Province and command of the Ten-Thousand Character Army, his surname now derived from his fief. Though he rose to prominence, his gifts were soon obscured by fortune's turning wheel.

    In his later years, Paper mastered the arts of longevity, weathering neither wind nor rain, unfeared by decay. When the sage Zuo Tai composed his great rhapsody on Chengdu, Paper beheld it once and held it forever in memory. His calligraphy, learned from Wang Xizhi, became the wonder of all under heaven.

    Serving the Prince of Liang, he compiled the Ancient Writings. Later, charged with editing the national histories alongside Wei Shou, he found his collaborator's prejudices troubling and requested to reconcile instead the accounts of expenditure and income—work at which he excelled greatly.

    Under the Chen sovereign, he dwelt in the company of courtiers and ladies of letters, composing verses in the Tower of Eternal Spring. Yet when the Sui armies approached and urgent messages came, Paper kept the seals closed—and thereby sealed the dynasty's fate.

    Under the Yangdi, he shared the emperor's favor with other scholars, composing lines on courtyard grass and swallows' nests, until the suspicious sovereign, brooding that none surpassed him, cast Paper into obscurity.

    With the Tang's rise came honor again—appointed Scholar-Official at the Hongwen Academy, he debated ancient wisdom with Chu Suoliang and Ouyang Xun, contributing to the enlightened governance of Zhen'guan. Later, when Sima Guang compiled his Comprehensive Mirror for Aid in Government, he valued Paper's erudition and consulted him often. Yet when Wang Anshi held sway and denounced the Spring and Autumn Annals as worthless scraps, Paper's objection earned him dismissal.

    When the Yuan arose, Paper abandoned his calling, becoming a merchant, his body burdened with coins, haunting teahouses and taverns, calculating profit by the smallest measure. How the people whispered! But when the Yuan fell and Paper entered service under the Ming, at last he received the recognition his life had long deserved. His descendants multiplied: some became historians, others poets; some recorded the accounts of treasure and grain, others the deeds of soldiers. All held office with honor, bearing the white sash of the ancients.

    Thus the Grand Historian reflects: The Duke of Zhou established the State of Cai to honor his brother, that noble lineage enduring through countless ages. Yet kingdoms rise and fall by the currents of fate. Cai, caught between the great powers, suffered invasion and ruin, yet its line never wholly perished. By the fall of Han, the name changed—from state to family, from family to multitude filling all under heaven. Of such transformations, none exceeds the House of Cai.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The nineteen brothers of Paper represent the nineteen leaves of paper that compose a single bound volume—a clever numerical conceit reflecting his essential nature.
  - key: ''
    value: In the late Yuan era, paper currency came into use, continuing through the Yuan dynasty itself. Such tender was called 'paper money,' a fitting testimony to Paper's enduring value.
